The `contradiction` tactic will use `h1` and `h2` to close the goal `False`.

The complete proof is concise because the contradiction is direct.
We could also have used `apply this` to `h1` to get `False`.
Or `exact this h1`.
Or `exfalso; exact this h1`.
Or `exfalso; apply this; exact h1`.

The `simpa` tactic is useful here. `simpa using X` is equivalent to `simp_all only [X]` in some cases, or more generally, `simp_all only [X]` if `X` is a function. Here `h` is a function, so `congr_fun h "hello"` is the right way to apply it. `simpa using congr_fun h "hello"` simplifies the result of applying `h` to "hello". It's a bit of a complex expression, so `simpa` is helpful. A simpler way would be:
```tactics
